<font color="#FF0000">TO COOK</font><br>
<tt>Sun Sep 14 13:46:12 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
You have made a very good point about being fearful and trembling. Is it realistic to think that any returning warriors would consider those who stayed behind as their equal? <br><br>
The war in Vietnam was different. It showed me that it was a war that should not have been fought - we have already discussed why I feel that way. Therefore, I don't consider those who stayed behind as being less than me. I accept Cook as being Cook, will you accept Tom as being Tom?<br><br>
No one ever spit on me. If they had I would have clocked them one. Even those of us who aspire to non violence have a boiling point. There are no excuses for *anyone* to spit on anyone. Returning vets, myself included, didn't do anything to deserve such treatment. Read Bob Green's *Homecoming* Half said they were spit upon, half said they were not. Who's to say? Possibly that could be a new thread subject? Our experiences coming home and whether or not we were abused. I am positive that you and I could find something to agree on there. Hurray!<br><br>
As I said I don't know what was in Barry Spatz's heart. Therefore, I can't say that I agree with you that he was one who thought the war wrong only because he was fearful. He has said that he never showed disdain for returning vets or called us &quot;baby killers&quot;.<br><br>
The problem arises when all who protested are lumped together and called, &quot;cowards&quot;. For there is the same stereotyping that continues to victimize veterans today. <br><br>
Those who left for Canada were faced with the same choice as I. The choice I made was the proper one for me. We know all of the arguments - it is doubtful that we will ever find the solution. <br><br>
Let me say this: I greatly admire your tenacity of spirit (I think Humming Eagle may have already said that), and I think that you and all the rest of us deserved better treatment when we arrived home. But, our achievements can't be diminished by the actions or, in the case of those who protested, the inaction of others. Be proud of your service as a Marine and as a law enforcement officer, and also know that you are welcome to fish on my side of the lake always.<br><br>
Will address your other post to me later, as I am missing Green Bay and Miami. Have other priorities you know.<br><br>
I agree that everyone at that time of military age was fearful. Same same as in WWII. 
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn,net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


